प्रत्यक्षात अशी दिसतेस?’( विनोद म्हणून हं),‘ सगळं आणलंय ना?’ ‘ जेवण खाली नेऊन ठेवा’ ‘ प्रसादाची ताटं कोणाला द्यायची?’ असे कितीतरी संवाद! एका खोलीत फोटोबूथसाठी डेकोरेशन तयार आणि कॅमेरामन, कॅमेरा घेऊन तयार! ‘ ए, आधी मास्क लावून फोटो’, ‘ आता मास्क काढून फोटो’ अशा त्याला सूचना! एकीकडे साग्रसंगीत, फेसबुक लाईव्ह पूजा, आणि दुसरीकडे पडद्यामागच्या volunteers ची लगबग चालू. रजिस्ट्रेशन करून घेणे, वाण देणे, फोटो काढणे, प्रसादाची ताटं तयार करणे, एक ना अनेक! ह्या सगळ्या गडबडीत वेळ कसा गेला ते कळलंच नाही, पूजा संपन्न झाली. आणि मग पडघम उठले ते ढोलताशाचे!! म्हणजे तर सोने पे सुहागा! एकंदरच देवळातल्या प्रसन्न वातावरणाने,अतिशय छान रीतीने संपन्न झालेल्या पूजेने ,आजूबाजूच्या हसऱ्या चेहऱ्यांनी मनाला नव्याने उभारी आली. आणि जेव्हा प्रत्यक्षात कार्यक्रम करायला मिळेल तेव्हा किती तयारी करावी लागेल, वातावरण कसं असेल ह्या सगळ्याची एक छानशी आनंददायी झलक मिळाली. ह्या कार्यक्रमासाठी ज्यांनी कष्ट घेतले त्या सर्व volunteers चे आणि दर्शनाला आलेल्या सर्व भक्तांचे आभार! लोभ आहेच तो वाढावा! ©️रश्मी चाफेकर महिला उपाध्यक्ष JOHN","languageCode":"und","legacyId":0,"id":"18335065|5382456618463537"},{"platformId":"503055433070371_5350813701627829","platform":"Facebook","date":"2021-04-08 00:03:43","updated":"2022-01-06 20:29:09","type":"photo","message":"Statement Supporting Water/Land Protectors Urging Biden Administration to Shut Down DAPL and Line 3 April 7, 2021 Caddo and Wichita Territory (Dallas, Texas): On Thursday, April 1, 2021, Indigenous youth held mass demonstrations in Washington D.C., urging the Biden administration to take swift action in shutting down the Dakota Access and Line 3 Pipelines, on the fifth anniversary of the founding of the Sacred Stone Camp, the first of a series of protest camps erected along the Missouri River in 2016. American Indian Heritage Day in Texas wants to express our support for those who demonstrated at the capitol in the name of “building back fossil free,” a future that imagines tribal sovereignty at the forefront of natural resource conservation and clean energy development. We do not believe that guarantees to clean drinking water, protection for American Indian sacred sites, or commitments to free, prior and informed consent are partisan issues. The contention surrounding the illegally-operating Dakota Access Pipeline is just as strong today as it was five years ago, especially for those living within the Oceti Sakowin, landowners in the area, and tribal members who never stopped the fight, long after the Sacred Stone and other camps were forcibly evicted at the beginning of Trump’s presidency. Youth continue to be leaders in Indigenous-led resistance to environmental desecration, today no less than in 2016 when dozens of Standing Rock youth ran to D.C. to deliver the same message to President Obama. The environmental and cultural threats associated with DAPL remain, and despite dwindling media coverage, tribes have continued the fight to protect their water, land, sacred sites. However, those urging pipeline shutdowns are now tackling two projects. Within the past week, we have witnessed Anishinaabe and other Indigenous water protectors and their allies forcibly removed from a traditional prayer lodge erected in the path of Enbridge’s Line 3 pipeline in Minnesota, Anishinaabe treaty territory. According to experts, if completed, Line 3 would endanger fragile ecosystems and Anishinaabe ways of life with approximately 750,000 gallons of Canadian tar sands oil running through it a day. Although Line 3 has been opposed for years by several northern Minnesota tribes, we believe that now is the time for President Biden to “stand with Indigenous people,” and reject projects that threaten tribal sovereignty to usher in a new era of reciprocal relationships between tribes and the United States.
